"1414","abt 1314":"about 1314","1314":"1314","1300":"1300","1362":"1362","1372":"1372","about 1300":"about 1300","1360":"1360","Kingsley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Kingsley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Bryn, Lancashire, England":"Bryn, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Kingsley, Cheshire, England":"Kingsley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gerard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Camille, Jean-Pierre, Murielle, Emile, Pascal, Pierre, Agathe, Alain, Aldes, Antoine, Armand.","French (<b>Gérard</b>), Walloon (mainly <b>Gérard</b>), and English (of Norman origin): from the personal name <i>Gérard</i>, <i>Gerard</i> (from Old French <i>Gerart</i>, <i>Girart</i>), composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. As a surname of French origin it is also found in Haiti. Compare   Garrard   and also French   Guerard  , English   Garard  ,   Gerrard  , and   Jarrard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerardi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Vito, Enzo, Gaspare, Luigi, Rocco, Antonio, Canio, Carmine, Filippo, Francesco, Giovanni, Libero.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gerardo</i> (see   Gerard  ). This surname is also found in southern France.","German and French (mainly Nord): Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from the personal name German   Gerhard  , French <i>Gérard</i> (see   Gerard  ), using the genitive of the Latinized form <i>Gerardus</i>."]},{"name":"Garrison","meanings":["English: from a shortened form of Middle English <i>Gerardson</i>, a patronymic from the personal name   Gerard   + <i>son</i>, or an Anglicized form of its Dutch cognate   Gerritsen  . The English surname is probably in most cases of Flemish or Dutch origin. It was brought to Britain by immigrants from the Low Countries, especially in the 15th and 16th centuries.","Americanized form of Jewish   Gerson   (see   Gershon  ).","Americanized form of Dutch   Gerritsen  ."]},{"name":"Garrard","meanings":["English (London and East Anglia): variant of   Gerard  .","Altered form of French <b>Gérard</b> (see   Gerard  ).","History: This surname (see 2 above) is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Geenen","meanings":["Dutch, Flemish, and North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Geen</i>, a pet form of   Gerard  ."]},{"name":"Gerardo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Francisco, Alberto, Alfredo, Aurelio, Carlos, Jesus, Juan, Norberto, Ramon, Tomas, Ana.  Italian Antonio, Carmine, Dino, Enrico, Marco, Marco Antonio.","Spanish and Italian: from the personal name <i>Gerardo</i> (see   Gerard  )."]},{"name":"Gerald","meanings":["English (of Norman origin); French (<b>Gérald</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gerald</i>, <i>Girald</i>, composed of the elements <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’ and <i>wald</i> ‘power, authority’. It was introduced to Britain by the Normans and was fairly common, but less so than   Gerard  , with which it was early confused. In France the much more common variants of this surname are <b>Géraud</b> and   Giraud  ."]},{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["English: variant of   Gerard  ."]},{"name":"Geron","meanings":["French (<b>Géron</b>): from the personal name <i>Gero</i>, <i>Gerone</i>, a short form of ancient Germanic names formed with the element <i>gār, gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’, as for example <i>Gérard</i> (see   Gerard  ).","Altered form of French <b>Guérin</b> (see   Guerin  ).","English (Lancashire): of Norman origin, from the personal name <i>Geron</i> of ancient Germanic origin, a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Gherardi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Silvio, Alessandro, Angelo, Antonio, Donato, Egidio, Ennio, Enzo, Gildo, Lucio, Luigi, Primo.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of <i>Gherardo</i>, one of themany Italian equivalents of   Gerard  ."]},{"name":"Garard","meanings":["English (London and Buckinghamshire): variant of   Gerard  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"FitzWilliam","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (of Norman origin): from Anglo-Norman French <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name   William  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"William FitzWilliam Gerard was born about 1300, in Kingsley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. He had